We visited Odori-ko in 2013 while they were still at the Waikiki location. That time they were GREAT. We just found out today that they moved to this new location about 4 years ago with a newer menu. This menu doesn't clearly distinguish which food items contain beef in the sauce vs not. Ex: chicken katsu curry has beef in the curry or yakiudon still has fish sauce and fish flakes even though it was requested to be made vegetarian without any meat.  Staff is nice to talk to and they remade the food. It would be easier for folks who don't eat all various types of meats to have clarification on the menu. Not only would it improve the customer experience, but also reduce food wastage. Really sad, but this place did not live up to it's expectations for us anymore :(

We used to visit Odori-ko in the former location in Kings Village, but what was the village is now a construction site. The founder, a sweet man, has passed, but his son has revived the restaurant in a new location. The new location lacks the foot traffic of the former Odori-ko, but it is more modern, brighter, roomier and still has the choices that his parent’s place had but now with a whole lot more innovative offerings. I expected to be disappointed, but actually, it was a wake up call to my tastebuds to pay attention. We both loved it and lingered partly because - and this is an experience not common in a sushi restaurant- we had more food than we could finish. The bright lights were nowhere near as charming as the old, dark tatami rooms of the old place, but, if anything, the food is as good or better. So happy we took a Lyft out to the new location!

It's hard to go wrong with sushi when you're in Hawaii, but if you're looking for an exceptional experience head to Odoriko.  Odoriko was recommended to us by a local. We went without reservations on a Thursday night and it was busy but we were seated quickly.  I can imagine on a Friday or Saturday you NEED a reservation though.  Our waiter was awesome.  Funny, nice, helpful, all around great guy.  We ended up getting 8 or 9 rolls, but hands down the Rainbow Roll was the best.  Yes it was a little pricey, but worth every penny.  Our waiter recommended eating the piece with the sweet shrimp on it last and I'm glad we listened to him.  If I could have gotten a whole roll with the sweet shrimp on it I would have.  If I go back to Honolulu I will definitely visit Odoriko again.  Worth every penny!
